re). Perhaps also from Warmington in Northamptonshire. The placenames derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrma</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matthew Worlington was born about 1218 as the son of William Worlington. He married Mrs Matthew Worlington before 1240, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1218–":"umbes 1218–Surnud","1218–Male":"1218–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","about 1218":"umbes 1218","1200":"1200","before 1240":"enne 1240","1240":"1240","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1218":"1218","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"about 1218–":"noin 1218–Kuollut","1218–Male":"1218–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","about 1218":"noin 1218","1200":"1200","before 1240":"ennen vuotta 1240","1240":"1240","about 1240":"noin 1240","1218":"1218","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"about 1218–":"environ 1218–Décédé","1218–Male":"1218–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée",